Roughly, we represent the top eight to 10% in the world when it comes to our financial ability.

03:38.259 --> 03:41.563
Now, I understand that in the economy where it doesn't always feel that way.

03:42.024 --> 03:43.666
You might be saying, listen, I'm like,

03:44.034 --> 03:45.676
I'm 35, 40 years old.

03:45.736 --> 03:49.942
I'm just trying to get like own a house, own a parking spot, own anything.

03:51.124 --> 03:53.547
And you say, it doesn't feel that way, but it is the truth.

03:53.707 --> 03:56.511
It is something that we have to recognize.

03:57.553 --> 04:05.945
And then what we saw up here was the top 1% and we recognize some of us even live in the top 1% of the world.

04:06.766 --> 04:12.754
And what happens is it doesn't seem to matter where we're at financially

04:13.186 --> 04:19.233
So often, we're looking at the person next to us and it doesn't feel like enough.

04:19.253 --> 04:21.736
Why doesn't it feel like enough?

04:22.937 --> 04:28.804
Why does it feel like no matter what we get, it never feels like enough?

04:30.165 --> 04:34.750
And maybe a deeper question is this, why don't you feel more content?

04:36.092 --> 04:41.458
Why do we spend so much of our lives feeling so discontent

04:41.986 --> 04:43.168
about what we have.

04:43.789 --> 04:53.482
When we look over at the person next to us, when we look at the person down the street, we make so much money, but it feels like, man, it doesn't matter how much money I make, it feels like I never have enough.

04:53.622 --> 04:56.466
Like, I'm always short, like, I'm never quite there.

04:56.526 --> 05:04.518
Or, man, it doesn't matter how much I make or what I purchase, there's always a friend, there's always a colleague who's doing better than I am.

05:04.778 --> 05:07.161
I mean, my brother-in-law, that guy drives me nuts.

05:07.181 --> 05:10.546
He's always talking about what car he drives and what cottage he bought.

05:10.626 --> 05:21.582
And for all of us, it doesn't matter where you're at financially, whether you're at your parents' place, waiting, man, I can't wait till I have my first apartment to, man, I've done really well, but I can always do better.

05:21.763 --> 05:27.411
There's part of us that says, man, it doesn't feel like enough, and we don't really feel content.

05:29.214 --> 05:31.257
That's what I wanna talk about in this series.

05:31.778 --> 05:34.101
I wanna talk our about our finances in this series.

05:34.121 --> 05:36.344
I wanna talk about money in this series.

05:36.385 --> 05:40.050
I wanna talk about what does it mean to actually find more contentment?

05:40.482 --> 05:41.043
in your life.

05:41.704 --> 05:45.609
What does it mean to actually find more meaning in your life, in your finances?

05:45.649 --> 05:48.653
What does it mean to find more freedom in your finances?

05:48.714 --> 05:53.460
What would it mean to be the generous person you actually want to be?

05:54.462 --> 06:03.494
And I want to let you know throughout this series, none of this series is about shame, none of this series is about guilt, none of this series is about forcing anybody to do anything.

06:03.735 --> 06:06.258
And the truth is we've all made financial

06:06.402 --> 06:11.269
decisions in our past that we regret, some of which we're reaping the consequences of even today.

06:11.329 --> 06:17.799
We all have things that we wish we were doing differently and we all have places where we feel like we don't measure up.

06:17.839 --> 06:24.569
But the goal at the end of this series would be for you to understand what contentment and meaning really mean.

06:25.430 --> 06:27.533
Now, Jesus talked about money all the time.

06:28.315 --> 06:33.362
And when Jesus talked about money, he talked often about the kingdom of God.

06:33.442 --> 06:38.727
this idea of like, man, when it comes to our resources, we want to be bringing heaven to earth.

06:39.127 --> 06:43.271
And he's talking about this in Matthew chapter six, and he talks about money, and he says this.

06:43.912 --> 06:52.960
He says, don't store up treasures here on earth where moths eat them and rust destroy them and where thieves break in and steal.

06:53.040 --> 07:00.047
He's saying, hey, listen, when it comes to your financial resources, don't invest in the things that waste away.

07:00.127 --> 07:03.250
Don't invest in the things that end up kind of

07:03.362 --> 07:08.712
being destroyed, invest in the things that really matter, that really make a difference.

07:09.613 --> 07:11.937
But so often we get caught up in it, don't we?

07:11.958 --> 07:20.232
We want to get this electronic, we need to get this car, we want to get this home, and we continue to look at the person next to us.

07:20.633 --> 07:22.777
And it's worse now than it ever was before.

07:23.118 --> 07:25.522
And if you feel that way, you're 100% right.

07:25.858 --> 07:30.623
There is a guy named Morgan Howsell who wrote a book called The Psychology of Money.

07:30.663 --> 07:32.185
Anybody read that book, Psychology of Money?

07:32.465 --> 07:35.709
If you haven't read it, it's a New York time bestseller, fantastic book.

07:35.989 --> 07:38.131
He has a book now called The Art of Spending Money.

07:38.192 --> 07:40.214
And he realized this.

07:41.035 --> 07:44.018
He said, man, something has changed in our culture, and it's this.

07:44.759 --> 07:48.763
On one hand, the richest are making more.

07:49.744 --> 07:51.346
And those with the lowest income,

07:51.618 --> 07:52.539
are making less.

07:52.599 --> 07:53.720
That's not news to you.

07:53.780 --> 07:57.985
You hear on the news all the time, there is a growing disparity in our culture.

07:58.486 --> 08:03.031
But at the same time, in 2010, as that was happening, something else happened.

08:04.072 --> 08:05.473
We all got on social media.

08:06.634 --> 08:10.859
And all of a sudden, not only is there a gap, but we can see it.

08:11.900 --> 08:12.841
I would sum it up this way.

08:13.342 --> 08:20.850
There's a growing wealth gap and constant exposure to how others live have created a contentment and comparison crisis

08:21.122 --> 08:22.164
in our culture.

08:23.506 --> 08:35.443
You sit on your couch, eating your cereal, watching your Netflix, scrolling on your phone, looking at Kim Kardashian's vacation, and thinking, man, that looks amazing.

08:36.364 --> 08:38.147
I wish I was on a vacation like that.

08:38.448 --> 08:40.050
How come she gets to go on that vacation?

08:40.290 --> 08:42.313
And you know what Kim Kardashian is doing by the pool?

08:42.874 --> 08:48.723
She's on her phone, looking at someone else's vacation, wondering, why can't I have a vacation like that?

08:49.464 --> 08:51.026
And that person is doing the same.

08:51.682 --> 09:00.594
And it's the same when it comes to where you live, same comes to the car you drive, same comes to the electronics you have in your life, same comes to the clothes you're wear.

09:00.654 --> 09:04.960
There's a constant comparison going on all the time.

09:05.340 --> 09:10.527
And as a result, we struggle with contentment.

09:10.547 --> 09:11.649
And so what do we do?

09:12.129 --> 09:15.153
We start to see what other people we have and we say, man, I deserve that.

09:15.214 --> 09:17.036
If they deserve it, I deserve it.

09:17.056 --> 09:18.858
If Drake has it, I should have it.

09:19.439 --> 09:19.619
Right?

09:19.680 --> 09:20.020
If Mr.

09:20.080 --> 09:21.522
Beast has it, I should have it.

09:22.082 --> 09:26.249
But it's also, man, I see this person who I know in my life.

09:27.370 --> 09:30.595
That person I went to university with, if they have it, I should have it.

09:30.655 --> 09:33.320
My neighbor has this, if they have it, I should have it.

09:34.762 --> 09:35.603
And I deserve it.

09:36.865 --> 09:40.731
And that's how you create a culture where everybody gets over their heads in debt.

09:41.733 --> 09:47.602
Because if I deserve it and I don't have the money for it, I'm gonna leverage what I can to get it.

09:48.258 --> 09:54.826
Morgan Haussel says this, he says, spending money to show people how much money you have is the fastest way to have less money.

09:57.969 --> 09:58.590
But we do it.

09:59.331 --> 10:02.514
We get caught in what I call the consumption cycle, right?

10:02.615 --> 10:03.896
It's that consumption cycle.

10:04.997 --> 10:16.050
You get your first place, your first apartment, and you're so excited, and you get your aunt's couch, and it's 50 years old, and you don't care, because it's yours.

10:16.706 --> 10:18.750
And she gives you money to take it.

10:18.790 --> 10:20.734
She says, whatever's in the questions, you can have it.

10:22.879 --> 10:26.386
And then after a while, you're online and you see, oh, your friends got that couch.

10:26.426 --> 10:27.207
And so what do you do?

10:27.267 --> 10:30.294
You go to IKEA and you get yourself a new couch.

10:30.895 --> 10:35.224
And you and your spouse have eight fights putting it together with one Allen key.

10:35.624 --> 10:36.466
But it's yours.

10:38.242 --> 10:39.083
And then what?

10:39.123 --> 10:41.727
You think, man, but we want to be real adulting.

10:41.827 --> 10:43.049
We want to be real adults.

10:43.069 --> 10:44.531
And what is a real adult?

10:44.852 --> 10:49.238
A real adult is someone who owns a sectional that their kids are not allowed to sit on, right?

10:49.298 --> 10:50.780
That's what that is.

10:52.763 --> 10:55.327
And we've got to one up, one more time, and we've got to one up.

10:55.407 --> 10:56.969
And we do it with everything.

10:57.250 --> 10:58.471
We do it with clothes.

10:58.932 --> 11:00.835
We do it with electronics.

11:00.855 --> 11:02.177
We do it with stuff.

11:02.297 --> 11:03.058
We do it with

11:03.138 --> 11:04.480
Vacation homes we do it.

11:04.500 --> 11:19.920
It doesn't matter who you are and it doesn't matter how much you have We get caught up in the consumption cycle and here's the problem the problem The problem is that your goal post keeps moving It never stops moving.

11:20.160 --> 11:24.145
It's designed that way So what's Jesus saying?

11:24.185 --> 11:27.730
When he says don't store up treasures here on earth

11:28.418 --> 11:32.683
where moth and rust destroy, because the minute you get that thing you want, you're going to want something else.

11:32.723 --> 11:35.666
And the minute you get that thing you want, you want something else.

11:35.686 --> 11:38.369
And I want you to be free of that.

11:40.151 --> 11:45.436
I want you to be free of the demand that never, ever, ever stops.

11:46.678 --> 11:47.679
So what do you do instead?

11:47.719 --> 11:54.226
He says this, instead store your treasures in heaven where moss and rust cannot destroy and these

11:54.370 --> 11:58.654
cannot break in, cannot destroy, and thieves do not break in, and steal.

11:59.375 --> 12:01.858
Invest in the things that really have eternal impact.

12:01.898 --> 12:04.020
Invest in the things that make a real difference.

12:04.060 --> 12:08.464
Invest in the things that will mean something into eternity.

12:09.385 --> 12:16.052
Man, when it comes to where you leverage your finances, look at the things that really last.

12:16.072 --> 12:22.098
Because at the end of the day, that huge walk-in closet you have is just going down the street to the thrift store one day.

12:24.386 --> 12:37.383
But the idea that you can invest in life change in people's lives, that you can invest in the lives of your kids, that you can invest in the life of your relationship with your spouse, these are the things that reverberate into heaven.

12:37.683 --> 12:40.427
What are you actually investing in?

12:41.528 --> 12:47.877
And then he says this, wherever your treasure is, there the desires of your heart will be also.

12:49.018 --> 12:51.922
And now he kind of gets to the crux of the whole thing.

12:53.250 --> 12:59.178
where your treasure is, where you invest your money, that's where your heart is gonna go.

13:00.059 --> 13:08.249
See, Jesus understands and he sees, Jesus sees the number, sees money as the number one competitor for your heart.

13:08.269 --> 13:11.333
And he knows that your heart will follow your money.

13:12.475 --> 13:21.426
If I gave you a hundred thousand dollars here today, which I'm not doing, just M&M's today, but if I gave you a hundred thousand dollars,

13:22.402 --> 13:24.825
And you said, man, you know what I'm going to do with that $100,000?

13:24.845 --> 13:26.487
I'm going to get my dream car.

13:28.069 --> 13:35.898
I'm willing to bet that my 16-year-old who just got his license, you're not going to let him test drive it for you here in the parking lot.

13:37.620 --> 13:39.302
Because, man, you've invested that money in.

13:39.322 --> 13:40.284
You're going to polish it.

13:40.464 --> 13:41.585
You're going to take care of it.

13:41.925 --> 13:43.447
That is where your heart will be.

13:43.688 --> 13:52.338
If you took that same $100,000 and you donated it to an orphanage in a country that really needs it, what would you be doing?

13:52.514 --> 13:54.016
Calling them to see how it's going.

13:54.337 --> 13:57.141
You'd be watching their social media online to see what's happening.

13:57.361 --> 13:58.703
You'd be checking in on them.

13:58.964 --> 14:00.145
You'd be praying for them.

14:00.546 --> 14:02.809
More than you'd be praying for your Lamborghini, I promise.

14:05.333 --> 14:08.858
See, your money is the steering wheel for your heart.

14:10.160 --> 14:19.474
That's why it's the number one thing I believe that you can actually, we're gonna talk about this more in this series, that you can actually leverage to grow spiritually.

14:21.218 --> 14:22.801
And then Jesus goes on to explain it more.

14:22.841 --> 14:27.109
He says this, your eye is like a lamp that provides light for your body.

14:27.169 --> 14:29.474
Now, why is he talking about eyes and lamps and lights?

14:29.514 --> 14:36.107
This is why, because in the time when Jesus is teaching this, people believed your eyes were the window to your soul.

14:36.147 --> 14:42.198
So if you had light eyes, light in your eyes, it meant you were a generous person.

14:42.259 --> 14:44.082
You were a person who looked at the world through

14:44.162 --> 14:46.024
the lens of abundance.

14:46.084 --> 14:47.285
That's how you saw the world.

14:47.525 --> 14:50.328
If you had dark eyes, you're a greedy person.

14:50.569 --> 14:52.290
You had a scarcity mentality.

14:52.611 --> 14:53.732
You were super cheap.

14:54.012 --> 14:56.515
That was dark eyes, dark eyes versus light eyes.

14:56.575 --> 15:00.078
And so he's saying, your eye is like a lamp that provides light to your whole body.

15:00.279 --> 15:03.562
When your eye is healthy, your whole body is filled with light.

15:03.822 --> 15:08.247
But when your eye is unhealthy, your whole body is filled with darkness.

15:10.269 --> 15:11.250
And then he says this,

15:11.650 --> 15:16.796
And if the light you think you have is actually darkness, how deep that darkness is.

15:16.856 --> 15:17.497
Here's a warning.

15:18.138 --> 15:21.062
If he says, hey, it's one thing to be generous.

15:22.043 --> 15:24.506
It's one thing to be selfish.

15:24.526 --> 15:28.471
It's one thing to tell people you're generous and then be selfish.

15:28.491 --> 15:29.912
That's the most dangerous of things.

15:31.294 --> 15:33.937
To tell people I'm a generous person.

15:33.997 --> 15:36.561
To tell people I have an abundance mentality.

15:36.601 --> 15:37.682
To tell people

15:37.794 --> 15:42.939
I'm excited to invest in the things of the kingdom and actually not do it in the background.

15:43.440 --> 15:45.782
How deep that darkness really is, he says.

15:47.624 --> 15:53.209
See, what Jesus is getting at here is how you handle your money starts to dictate how you see the world.

15:54.290 --> 16:04.060
The more you see the world through self, the more you're selfish with your finances, the more you see the world as having a scarcity mentality, the less generous you are.

16:04.320 --> 16:06.482
That's the way you start to see the world.

16:07.074 --> 16:11.519
That's the way you start to see your relationships with your friends and your kids and your family.

16:11.719 --> 16:15.223
And how you handle your money also dictates how you see God.

16:17.145 --> 16:20.389
If you say, man, God, I'm not going to trust you with any of my finances.

16:20.429 --> 16:21.871
This is all for me to decide.

16:22.671 --> 16:24.413
This is I need to control things.

16:24.714 --> 16:25.955
I'm not going to pray about things.

16:26.055 --> 16:29.139
I'm going to try to earn enough money so I don't have these problems anymore.

16:29.379 --> 16:30.720
I don't need to trust in you, God.

16:30.921 --> 16:32.082
What I need is more money.

16:32.603 --> 16:35.666
If I have more money, then my life would be more in control.

16:36.898 --> 16:45.652
And Jesus is saying, man, I think if you trusted me, I think if you opened your Bible, your life would be more in control because it would be in my control.

16:47.054 --> 16:51.040
How you handle your money dictates how you see God.

16:52.342 --> 16:54.065
And this happens to us all the time.

16:54.345 --> 16:59.614
And the reason is because you have an internal money story.

17:00.194 --> 17:00.535
You do.

17:02.037 --> 17:03.940
What is your internal money story?

17:03.960 --> 17:05.042
I want you to think about this.

17:05.378 --> 17:11.648
It usually comes from your childhood, how you were brought up, and you can probably put together what it was.

17:11.728 --> 17:16.315
My dad grew up in rural Ontario.

17:16.776 --> 17:19.160
His mom immigrated from Northern Ireland.

17:19.761 --> 17:23.887
They tried to start a farm together, their family, very little income.

17:23.948 --> 17:28.455
My dad had two outfits, one for school and church, and one for work at home.

17:28.535 --> 17:29.556
Those were his two outfits.

17:30.117 --> 17:33.042
When he played soccer with his friends, they had soccer shoes,

17:33.218 --> 17:35.461
He had his dad's old Sunday shoes.

17:35.541 --> 17:36.202
That's what he wore.

17:37.524 --> 17:41.389
And so my dad knows how to make a dollar go a long way.

17:42.510 --> 17:53.484
My dad, you could argue, has a scarcity mentality when it comes to funds, except in his family, they were incredibly generous and involved in their church.

17:54.485 --> 17:59.832
So I grew up and I saw, man, my dad is so generous to the church.

18:00.053 --> 18:01.234
And I also saw,

18:01.730 --> 18:04.835
Man, it's hard to get your allowance raised around here.

18:08.019 --> 18:09.562
But doesn't that start to shape me?

18:10.062 --> 18:12.726
Like I'm lying to myself if I said that doesn't shape me.

18:13.968 --> 18:18.475
I'm lying to myself if I said that hasn't impacted how I see the world.

18:19.977 --> 18:22.802
How you handle money impacts how you see the world.

18:23.022 --> 18:25.305
How you handle money impacts how you see God.

18:25.766 --> 18:27.188
How you handle money.

18:28.831 --> 18:31.154
Think about this for some of you.

18:31.586 --> 18:43.019
dictates how your kids see the world, and how your kids see God, and how you talk about money in front of your kids dictates how they see the world around them.

18:43.039 --> 18:44.301
So what's your money story?

18:45.282 --> 18:46.263
How do you see money?

18:46.724 --> 18:48.426
Let me give some examples of what I'm talking about.

18:49.287 --> 18:52.010
Scarcity or abundance, how do you see it?

18:53.111 --> 18:55.594
Security, man, I need money to feel secure.

18:55.714 --> 18:59.058
If I just have enough money, then I'll feel secure, or

18:59.330 --> 19:01.313
Trust, I trust God's gonna show up.

19:01.373 --> 19:03.275
I trust God's gonna be here for me.

19:03.295 --> 19:04.157
Is it ownership?

19:04.217 --> 19:10.185
Hey, this money that I have, I own it, this is mine, it's no one else's, or is it stewardship?

19:10.205 --> 19:12.969
This is God's money, and I'm just here to manage it well.

19:14.090 --> 19:15.272
Is it status?

19:15.612 --> 19:19.818
The possessions that I have are about status in my life, or is it service?

19:20.058 --> 19:25.145
My finances are here to serve, to serve my family, to serve my kids, to serve the people around me.

19:25.406 --> 19:26.908
How do you see money?

19:27.188 --> 19:28.690
Because how do you see money?

19:29.666 --> 19:33.810
dictates how you see the world, and it ultimately dictates how you see God.

19:34.971 --> 19:49.785
I would argue if you wanna diagnose where you're at with God, your credit card bill is a pretty good place to start, because it gives you a pretty good indication of what you trust in, what you value, where your heart is.

19:51.226 --> 19:57.573
And then he says this, no one can serve two masters, for you will hate one and love the other.

19:57.893 --> 19:59.154
You'll be devoted to one

19:59.394 --> 20:00.395
and despise the other.

20:00.676 --> 20:03.340
You cannot serve God and be enslaved to money.

20:03.420 --> 20:06.384
This translation for money actually is better translated.

20:06.765 --> 20:10.610
Mammon who was like a God of the time, like an idol of the time.

20:10.650 --> 20:16.138
And man was the idol of greed and the idol of like more, more and more and the idol.

20:16.258 --> 20:18.382
I'm going to do whatever it takes to get mine.

20:18.402 --> 20:23.990
And Jesus is saying, listen, you can't serve God and serve Mammon at the same time.

20:25.111 --> 20:26.994
It's just impossible to do.

20:27.426 --> 20:30.491
You can't say, man, I love God, God, my heart.

20:30.511 --> 20:38.864
You know, when I, whenever I say, hey, if I said to you, if I could say to this whole room, how many of you have a sin you want to confess?

20:38.904 --> 20:41.408
And you would say, oh yeah, we all have sin, we need to confess.

20:41.868 --> 20:43.511
I'd say, what is your confession?

20:43.972 --> 20:47.657
What do you think is the percentage of people in this room who would say greed?

20:49.260 --> 20:51.503
It's probably zero, 1%.

20:52.945 --> 20:55.890
So many of us don't think about this.

20:56.194 --> 21:00.939
We don't think about man, am I caught up in a consumption-based life?

21:02.181 --> 21:05.384
Because we've always got someone else to look at who's got more than we have.

21:05.965 --> 21:07.487
It's not me who struggles with greed.

21:07.527 --> 21:08.568
It's Kim Kardashian.

21:08.768 --> 21:09.409
She's the one.

21:10.210 --> 21:11.531
Look at her Instagram profile.

21:13.914 --> 21:23.044
He's saying, man, if you're going to spend your life consuming, you can't serve me and be and serve Mammon at the same time.

21:23.184 --> 21:24.946
If you're going to spend your life consuming,

21:25.858 --> 21:26.959
you're gonna be consumed.

21:28.121 --> 21:29.543
That's what this is really all about.

21:29.563 --> 21:33.989
That a conception first life leaves you consumed.

21:34.149 --> 21:35.852
I have been preaching this for years.

21:36.072 --> 21:38.075
It is 100% true.

21:40.478 --> 21:51.673
It is so interesting to me to see how easily it is for us to get caught up in this and how easy it is for me to get caught up in this.

21:52.474 --> 21:55.378
For me to feel like, no, I'm on top of this and then

21:55.554 --> 21:57.236
I see the next shiny thing.

21:58.517 --> 22:00.419
And I go, oh man, that would be nice.

22:01.560 --> 22:04.383
You know, I've confessed my countertop addiction here before.

22:05.545 --> 22:08.588
But you know, you see that kitchen, it's like, I'm good with my kitchen countertop.

22:08.628 --> 22:09.329
And then what?

22:09.349 --> 22:10.590
I see another countertop.

22:12.072 --> 22:13.513
And I go, oh man, wouldn't that be nice?

22:14.594 --> 22:15.735
But you know what happens, right?

22:16.276 --> 22:19.019
Well, you can't put that countertop on a crappy set of cabinets.

22:19.499 --> 22:22.002
And you can't put those cabinets on a crappy floor.

22:22.690 --> 22:25.113
And you can't put in that crappy floor without what?

22:25.213 --> 22:30.098
New molding, because at the end of the day, we'll get it out of the house when we sell it.

22:31.580 --> 22:36.285
Or whatever I need to do to tell myself to keep consuming.

22:37.286 --> 22:39.849
And the interesting thing is who are we comparing to?

22:40.309 --> 22:42.051
This to me is the most interesting thing.

22:42.531 --> 22:48.658
We compare to people all the time, but we only compare the money part, right?

22:48.962 --> 23:01.053
So we look at Elon Musk, or we look at Jeff Bezos, and we look at those people and go, oh wow, but we're only looking at the money part of their life because we're thinking consumption, but we're not looking at their whole life, are we?

23:01.754 --> 23:11.203
You know that the top 10 richest people in the world combined have 13 divorces between them.

23:11.223 --> 23:18.610
Jimmy Carr, who's, anybody fall Jimmy Carr, he's like a comedian, Jimmy Carr, he's not the cleanest comedian, I'll be honest, but he says this, he says,

23:19.234 --> 23:20.976
Everyone is jealous of what you've got.

23:20.996 --> 23:22.557
No one is jealous of how you got it.

23:25.180 --> 23:28.063
People look at his wealth and think, oh man, I want that.

23:28.083 --> 23:30.485
And he's like, you don't know the road I took.

23:31.065 --> 23:32.787
You don't know the sacrifice I made.

23:33.248 --> 23:36.090
My relationship with my spouse or my relationship with my kids.

23:36.471 --> 23:37.992
You don't know anything about me.

23:38.232 --> 23:40.695
All you see is my highlight reel.

23:41.756 --> 23:44.659
Because isn't that what we're comparing to you every single day?

23:47.081 --> 23:48.242
And then Jesus says this.

23:49.602 --> 23:53.646
He says, that's why I tell you, guys, don't worry about everyday life.

23:54.407 --> 23:56.369
And then you can read this for yourself.

23:56.449 --> 23:58.932
Jesus gets into it like it's all poetic all of a sudden.

23:59.593 --> 24:01.915
He's like, look at the birds of the field.

24:02.796 --> 24:04.758
They don't worry, right?

24:04.798 --> 24:08.442
They're not comparing Instagram profiles of who has the nicest nest.

24:09.564 --> 24:12.447
They're not worried about what seed's gonna be on the ground.

24:13.207 --> 24:14.389
They know I'm gonna provide.

24:15.009 --> 24:16.111
They're chill the birds.

24:17.452 --> 24:19.314
He says, look at the lilies of the field.

24:19.970 --> 24:24.596
They're better dressed and more beautiful than King Solomon.

24:24.636 --> 24:27.801
He talks about the wisest king and his beautiful robes.

24:28.962 --> 24:30.505
He's like, what are you worried about?

24:30.525 --> 24:39.557
And he says this, and if God cares so wonderfully for wildflowers that are here today and thrown into the fire tomorrow, he will certainly care for you.

24:39.958 --> 24:42.060
Why do you have so little?

24:42.401 --> 24:43.342
And then this is interesting.

24:43.523 --> 24:46.066
Does this say why you have so little contentment?

24:46.562 --> 24:49.647
He doesn't say, why do you have so little patience?

24:49.707 --> 24:54.775
He doesn't say, why do you have so little money or possessions or anything like that?

24:54.855 --> 24:59.081
He says, why do you have so little faith?

24:59.101 --> 25:02.687
Where is your trust that I'm enough?

25:04.169 --> 25:07.354
Where is your trust that I will give you enough?

25:09.177 --> 25:12.241
Now here's the question, how much is enough?

25:14.585 --> 25:15.346
How much is enough?

25:16.098 --> 25:19.784
See, contentment isn't about how much you have.

25:20.826 --> 25:22.428
It's about who defines enough.

25:24.451 --> 25:26.595
Who defines what is enough in your life?

25:29.680 --> 25:35.830
For many of us, the world around us is defining for us what's enough.

25:35.850 --> 25:43.442
We believe what the world tells us about enough, and you'll never have enough if that's the way you run your life, and you'll never be enough.

25:46.018 --> 25:48.502
But what does God say about what is enough?

25:49.343 --> 25:51.446
What does God say about what is enough for you?

25:51.526 --> 25:52.267
What does God say?

25:52.547 --> 25:56.032
What do you say about your life and what is enough?

25:57.174 --> 25:58.376
This is an important question.

25:58.436 --> 26:00.218
Morgan Haussel says this, he says, you know what?

26:00.499 --> 26:04.284
The hardest financial skill is getting the goalposts to stop moving.

26:05.005 --> 26:08.630
The hardest financial skill is to say, this is enough.

26:09.952 --> 26:11.434
I have decided what enough is.

26:12.256 --> 26:13.938
I don't need any more than this.

26:14.594 --> 26:16.777
I don't need 100 outfits.

26:18.059 --> 26:19.121
This car is enough.

26:20.142 --> 26:21.063
Renting is enough.

26:22.205 --> 26:26.391
But what Jesus is saying, what if trusting me to define what is enough for you?

26:26.772 --> 26:31.899
Do you trust that I will always be enough, that I will always provide?

26:33.041 --> 26:38.388
He says this, so don't worry about these things saying, what will we eat or what will we drink or what will we wear?

26:38.448 --> 26:42.354
These things dominate the thoughts of unbelievers, but your Heavenly Father

26:42.594 --> 26:45.077
already knows all your needs.

26:46.298 --> 26:47.139
He already knows.

26:49.122 --> 26:52.466
See, contentment isn't found in having more.

26:52.826 --> 26:56.110
It's found in trusting that God is enough.

26:57.672 --> 27:00.515
That He's enough, and He'll provide enough.

27:02.177 --> 27:09.906
And then He says this, seek the kingdom of God above all else and live righteously, and He will give you everything you

27:10.242 --> 27:12.727
Now he's back to, man, where are you investing?

27:12.868 --> 27:14.672
What is your treasure?

27:14.852 --> 27:16.656
Are you investing in things of the kingdom?

27:16.896 --> 27:18.239
Are you investing in relationship?

27:18.299 --> 27:19.983
Are you investing in life change?

27:20.384 --> 27:23.250
Are you investing in the things that really matter?

27:24.514 --> 27:34.147
Seeing people baptize, seeing people find Jesus, investing in your kids that you might build a relationship with them that they might find Jesus, investing in a relationship with Jesus yourself.

27:34.407 --> 27:39.935
Man, these are the things that moth won't destroy and rust can't destroy and are not going away.

27:40.275 --> 27:43.700
Nobody will ever take my relationship with Jesus to the thrift store.

27:43.720 --> 27:44.882
That's never happening.

27:46.884 --> 27:48.086
That's never happening.

27:49.428 --> 27:51.150
It doesn't matter how little I have.

27:51.210 --> 27:54.034
You cannot take that away from me.

27:54.114 --> 27:55.195
And that is enough.

27:57.559 --> 28:00.743
And that's what I want my kids to have, right?

28:01.324 --> 28:09.655
More than the latest cell phone, and a great job, and a good car, and a nice house, and all the stuff that's gonna go away.

28:09.695 --> 28:13.700
What's he saying?

28:13.720 --> 28:22.572
He's saying, listen, Jeff, a consumption of first life leaves you consumed, but a kingdom first life is what leaves you content.

28:22.592 --> 28:23.954
Seeking the things of God.

28:24.610 --> 28:27.534
Contentment isn't found in having more.

28:27.875 --> 28:33.142
It's found in trusting that God is enough.

28:34.904 --> 28:37.889
That God is enough for you and for me.

28:39.751 --> 28:41.754
I'm super passionate about this topic.

28:42.074 --> 28:42.715
And here's why.

28:42.735 --> 28:43.697
I want to share with you why.

28:44.458 --> 28:46.180
I've been at this church for 17 years.

28:47.081 --> 28:49.164
In a number of years, I became the exec director.

28:49.285 --> 28:53.170
And that meant that I got to,

28:53.314 --> 28:55.157
got the privilege of overseeing the finances.

28:56.118 --> 29:00.145
And so I knew, I knew and I know what people give financially in this church.

29:02.068 --> 29:04.291
And the first time I'd ever been exposed to that.

29:05.453 --> 29:07.316
And here's the number one thing I learned.

29:08.918 --> 29:14.507
When I looked at the people, some people who were just incredibly generous, this is what I learned.

29:15.889 --> 29:18.994
There was a strong correlation between those people

29:20.226 --> 29:23.810
and the people who you look to and go, man, I would like to be like them.

29:25.292 --> 29:27.235
And this is the thing that surprised me.

29:28.937 --> 29:32.601
I started to go to their homes to visit them sometimes, just for church stuff.

29:34.003 --> 29:35.405
These people weren't living in mansions.

29:36.466 --> 29:38.128
These people weren't driving sports cars.

29:40.271 --> 29:49.042
These people were living in modest homes with modest means, and they're incredibly generous people.

29:50.498 --> 30:04.273
And I was like, man, when people in our church say, I want to be like so and so, this is like one of the big common denominators that their people have decided, listen, I only need so much to live.

30:04.453 --> 30:07.136
There is a line that God has called me to that is enough.

30:07.837 --> 30:11.761
And beyond that, I have the margin to invest in kingdom things.

30:12.622 --> 30:15.205
I have the margin to make a difference in people's lives.

30:18.608 --> 30:20.050
And I've had the opportunity

30:20.866 --> 30:23.670
to work at a church where everybody lived in those mansions.

30:25.473 --> 30:29.018
And I've had the opportunity to serve at churches where people had nothing.

30:30.080 --> 30:32.423
And I've had the opportunity to serve in this church.

30:32.583 --> 30:40.795
And what I've learned is the people understand what is enough and what a life of generosity is are the people that you want to be like.

30:41.997 --> 30:42.438
I know that.

30:43.239 --> 30:47.265
I'm not saying that's easy, not at all, but it's true.

30:49.068 --> 30:50.770
I don't get paid to tell you the easy thing.

30:52.514 --> 30:53.896
I get paid to tell you the true thing.

30:55.678 --> 30:56.660
Let me ask you this question.

30:58.122 --> 31:01.807
If you lived on a deserted island where no one could see you, how would you live?

31:03.529 --> 31:06.674
If you knew no one could see you, there's nobody compared to you.

31:06.694 --> 31:07.515
There's nobody around.

31:07.575 --> 31:09.017
Just you on a deserted island.

31:09.337 --> 31:10.078
How would you live?

31:10.759 --> 31:14.745
You might say, oh, well, you know, I'd have a mansion with 10 rooms.

31:14.825 --> 31:15.146
Would you?

31:15.186 --> 31:16.047
You got to clean that.

31:16.067 --> 31:17.168
It's just you on the island.

31:19.391 --> 31:21.234
You say, oh, yeah, actually, that's true.

31:21.378 --> 31:22.540
How many beds can I sleep in?

31:24.102 --> 31:24.683
Like one bed.

31:24.703 --> 31:26.986
I need one room.

31:28.168 --> 31:28.789
What would you eat?

31:28.809 --> 31:31.914
Oh my gosh, I would eat this and that.

31:31.994 --> 31:33.056
But you know what would happen.

31:33.096 --> 31:34.498
Eventually it's going to boil down to what?

31:34.898 --> 31:36.961
Kind of five meals that you'd eat most of the time.

31:39.145 --> 31:42.410
What kind of car would you drive if nobody cared and nobody could see?

31:44.373 --> 31:45.294
How much would it matter?

31:46.556 --> 31:48.018
It's an interesting question, isn't it?

31:48.674 --> 31:52.779
It starts to get down to what really, truly is enough.

31:55.202 --> 31:59.206
I've got a bit of an exercise for the brave people here if you want to do that this week.

32:00.027 --> 32:05.253
And it's this, I want you to make, this is like, I taught grade 10 business a long time ago.

32:05.313 --> 32:07.496
So this is as simple as this is a grade 10 business right here.

32:08.797 --> 32:11.360
What are your needs and what are your wants?

32:11.500 --> 32:12.642
Now, I want you to be careful.

32:12.662 --> 32:16.306
You're going to list your needs and you're going to list your wants, but be careful.

32:16.802 --> 32:21.386
because our culture is really good at marketing your wants as needs, right?

32:22.648 --> 32:24.770
So you've got to be really careful, right?

32:24.850 --> 32:31.016
Maybe you would say, well, the internet is in need, but add free Spotify, that's a want, people, okay?

32:34.399 --> 32:39.464
And if you said, man, what do I actually, like, what do I actually need?

32:41.406 --> 32:42.387
Because it says, what?

32:42.407 --> 32:45.490
My God will supply all of your needs.

32:46.658 --> 32:48.160
What do I actually need?

32:49.461 --> 32:52.926
To me, this is a very freeing exercise.

32:55.008 --> 32:59.093
Because you'll realize that, man, what do I really need?

32:59.253 --> 33:00.715
I need like a roof over my head.

33:00.755 --> 33:04.440
And honestly, I don't need to own that roof.

33:05.801 --> 33:08.905
If I had a roof over my head and I could rent that roof, that's also great.

33:10.207 --> 33:13.010
But sometimes what, we get caught up in the lie that, oh,

33:13.090 --> 33:16.034
I got to own that roof and what we over leverage ourselves.

33:16.194 --> 33:24.546
And then when we get in that situation, we get more house than we can afford because, you know, we need a big kitchen because we entertain, but how often have you had anybody over?

33:24.627 --> 33:28.973
Be careful.

33:30.014 --> 33:32.678
If you boiled it down to your basic needs, what are they?

33:34.360 --> 33:41.010
And for many of you, if you said, man, if that's really all I needed and all the wants went away,

33:41.954 --> 33:43.035
Man, I'd be okay.

33:44.297 --> 33:50.305
And then the question becomes, man, if that's true and you had all of that margin left, what could you do with it?

33:51.687 --> 33:52.789
What could you do in your life?

33:53.289 --> 33:55.672
How could you invest it in kingdom things in your family?

33:55.692 --> 33:57.455
How can you invest it in kingdom things with your friends?

33:57.495 --> 33:59.237
How could you invest it in the work of God?

33:59.518 --> 34:00.879
What could you see?

34:01.080 --> 34:03.663
And then what I want you to do is make a list.

34:03.823 --> 34:05.626
This is two part homework, okay?

34:06.687 --> 34:07.348
This is enough.

34:08.049 --> 34:08.850
This is enough.

34:09.058 --> 34:09.639
list.

34:09.659 --> 34:11.803
And it can be like, hey, this is enough.

34:12.845 --> 34:15.209
I am drawing the line for an, I mean, God is enough.

34:15.950 --> 34:16.932
I hope you heard that today.

34:17.553 --> 34:21.620
But this is an exercise for you to just look at, okay, what's actually enough for me?

34:23.263 --> 34:25.708
And for maybe it's enough for you, it's an enough income.

34:25.788 --> 34:27.110
This is enough income for me.

34:27.130 --> 34:28.272
I'm not beyond.

34:28.292 --> 34:29.394
This is all margin.

34:29.634 --> 34:31.576
This is all opportunity to make a difference.

34:31.596 --> 34:36.141
This is all an opportunity to do the things that really matter, that rust and moth cannot destroy.

34:36.462 --> 34:39.625
I cannot tell you the freedom that comes from an exercise like this.

34:40.186 --> 34:42.789
And this comes from a recovering countertop addict, right?

34:49.837 --> 34:55.123
That doesn't really matter how nice my coach is.

34:56.124 --> 34:58.226
It doesn't really matter how nice your coach is.

34:59.170 --> 35:03.558
You can say it's an investment, all you want, it's not, right?

35:04.380 --> 35:06.363
I remember helping a friend move.

35:07.626 --> 35:09.690
And this is what he said to me, man, we had to sell this house.

35:10.712 --> 35:12.335
And he said, but this coach is the problem.

35:12.475 --> 35:14.118
And I said, well, what's the problem with the coach?

35:14.799 --> 35:16.142
He's like, well, I don't know what to do with it.

35:16.162 --> 35:17.424
I'm still making payments on it.

35:17.464 --> 35:18.667
It doesn't fit in the next house.

35:21.632 --> 35:22.674
But it was an investment.

35:24.738 --> 35:26.260
This is our forever coach.

35:26.280 --> 35:29.445
We tell ourselves so many stories to justify spending money.

35:32.470 --> 35:36.877
So this is installment one, and we really want to help you.

35:36.977 --> 35:41.704
And there's something I am really excited about that I want you to go and check out, and it's this.

35:42.385 --> 35:53.362
If you go to connectstchurch.com slash sweet spot, we have put so many great resources, podcasts, books there, not just Christian books, like other stuff,

35:53.474 --> 36:01.304
all kinds of stuff, the best of stuff, the podcast, podcasts, links to direct episodes, books that you can read.

36:01.424 --> 36:05.470
And there is actually a 15-day journey that starts tomorrow.

36:05.810 --> 36:12.078
If you want to go on it with us, short devotional readings, a 15-day journey to more contentment and generosity in your life.

36:13.099 --> 36:15.703
